WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello and welcome to 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Neil.

6
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Now it's Christmas time in the UK at the moment.

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And like with celebrations around the world,

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
lots of people have many happy memories about Christmas.

9
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Beth, do you have any happy Christmas memories?

10
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I have a lot.

11
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
My cousins and I used to always put on a Christmas performance for the family.

12
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
That was always fun.

13
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
What about you?

14
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Christmas was magical.

15
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I lived in Canada when I was a kid and it was always snowing,

16
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
so it just felt perfect.

17
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Amazing.

18
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Well, at this time of year, we might look back at the Christmas's from the past,

19
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
from our childhood,

20
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and feel like they were happier or more magical than Christmas fields today.

21
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Yes, thinking about the past can make us feel happy and sad at the same time.

22
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
It's a strange feeling we call nostalgia.

23
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And we're going to be talking about nostalgia today,

24
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
as well as Christmas memories and traditions.

25
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases.

26
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
You can practice these with the quiz and the worksheets on our website.

27
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Go to BBCLearningEnglish.com

28
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
First, Beth, I have a question for you.

29
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
In the UK, the most popular Christmas meal is a roast turkey.

30
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Oh, yes, and all the roast potatoes and Brussels sprouts.

31
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
That's right, yes, but which of these has become a popular food

32
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000
to eat at Christmas time in Japan?

33
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Is it a turkey ramen, b fried chicken, or c take away pizza?

34
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
I think the answer is fried chicken.

35
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Well, we'll find out at the end of the program.

36
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Now, at Christmas, people often create family traditions that they repeat every year.

37
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Common traditions in the UK include putting out a snack for father Christmas

38
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
that Santa Claus who delivers presents for children.

39
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Well, here is host of BBC Radio Force all in the mind, Claudia Hammond,

40
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
talking to psychology professor Darrell O'Connor about his Christmas traditions.

41
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Hello, Darrell.

42
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
I wonder whether you think nostalgia for Christmas past influences your Christmas present.

43
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Well, indeed it does, Claudia.

44
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
So actually, I look back on my childhood Christmas.

45
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Lots and lots of nostalgia.

46
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
So when I was a child, every single Christmas morning,

47
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
we would have to queue up on the stairs.

48
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And my father would go into the front room of the house.

49
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Just to double check.

50
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Just to kiss Santa Claus was still there.

51
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And we had it wet.

52
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And then, of course, I have repeated that exact same thing for my children.

53
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
They line up on the stairs as well, how sweet.

54
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Dying for their presence.

55
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
When Claudia asked Darrell whether nostalgia influences his present day

56
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Christmas's Darrell response indeed it does.

57
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.000
This is a common conversational way to say yes or agree with someone.

58
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
We say, indeed, followed by do in the present tense.

59
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
On Christmas morning, Darrell asks his children to queue up on the stairs,

60
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.000
so he can check for Santa Claus, just like Darrell's father did when he was small.

61
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
And Claudia likes this tradition, imagining the children waiting on the stairs,

62
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
dying for their presence.

63
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
We use the phrase dying for informally when someone really wants something.

64
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Now, when we remember Christmas from the past and feel nostalgia,

65
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
we often remember things in a very positive way.

66
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
But was the past definitely better?

67
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Are we remembering correctly?

68
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
This is what Claudia Hammond asked Katherine Loveday, who's a professor of cognitive neuroscience

69
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
on BBC Radio 4 program all in the mind.

70
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
How accurate are nostalgic memories on the accurate?

71
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Well, they're often going to be rose-tinted and made more positive, of course,

72
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
and that's what we do with our past generally.

73
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
It doesn't really matter. I mean, in our work, we just shown that the function of memory

74
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
is not about accuracy. It doesn't matter if some of the details are wrong.

75
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
It doesn't matter how we frame it. In fact, it's actually better for us in a way,

76
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
to reframe our memories and to slightly adjust them to suit who we are now.

77
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Katherine says that our memories are often rose-tinted.

78
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
If a memory is rose-tinted, we only see the positive things about it,

79
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
and don't remember any of the bad parts.

80
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
But according to Katherine, it doesn't always matter. She says the function of memory is not accuracy.

81
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Function means the purpose of something.

82
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
In fact, Katherine says that how we frame a memory doesn't matter.

83
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Frame can be used as a verb to mean how we think of or describe something like a memory.

84
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
So our memories aren't that accurate.

85
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And it isn't that important, unless, of course, we need to remember factual details about something important.

86
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So, Anna, Stalja, about Christmas memories, might not be based on what things were actually like in the past.

87
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
But we shouldn't worry too much.

88
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And I think it's time I revealed the answer to my quiz question, Beth.

89
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
I asked, what has become a traditional food to eat in Japan at Christmas time?

90
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And I said, fried chicken was I right?

91
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
You are absolutely correct.

92
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with nostalgia,

93
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.000
a feeling of happiness and also some sadness when you think about a thing that happened in the past.

94
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The phrase, indeed, followed by the present simple form of do, can be used informally instead of answering yes.

95
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
For example, Beth, do you enjoy eating Brussels sprouts at Christmas?

96
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Indeed, I do.

97
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Dying for something is an informal phrasal verb we use to say that we really want something.

98
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Rose tinted means seeing only the positive parts of something and not the bad parts.

99
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Function means the purpose of something.

100
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.000
And frame can be used as a verb to mean how we think of or describe something.

101
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

102
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Test why you've learned in the episode with the quiz and worksheets on our websites.

103
00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:17.000
To all our listeners who are celebrating Christmas, Merry Christmas, and we hope you all have a good end to the year.

104
00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:18.000
See you soon.

105
00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Bye!

106
